[02:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ability to drag this little slider, and we can select the frame that we want to edit. So let\'s say about 2/3 through the video, we found a frame that we really like. Well, now you have the ability to'

[02:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actually edit that frame. So you can do that with a prompt or you can do it with images and a prompt. You have the ability to upload your own assets. For our example, I\'m going to keep it pretty basic and I\'m going to say a massive'

[02:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'alien spaceship is burning and falling from the sky. Basically, I want it to crash in the background of this footage. And I also prompted in that I don\'t want any of the framing or composition to change. I only want the spaceship to be'

[02:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'inserted into [music] the scene. Now, from here, you have a drop-own menu where you can select a wide variety of different image editing tools. You have Nano Banana Pro, GPT2, Flex 2 Max. There\'s quite a few options'

[02:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that are available to you inside of the menu. I\'m going to stick with Nano Banana Pro, but GPT image 2 is also very, very good. And when you\'re ready, all you have to do is click generate frame. Now, this is different than using'

[03:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'other video-based Omni models where you typically would hit render and then it would actually create the video footage. That can be helpful, but it can get quite expensive, especially if you are having to wait for 5 to 10 minutes to'

[03:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'see the result and then go back and forth and edit. Not only does it financially add up, it also adds up from a time perspective. And when you\'re working on an AI video project, it\'s all about saving as much time as possible.'

